{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "The agency essentially became a lobbyist for its clean-water cause by directing people to advocacy organizations, the Government Accountability Office said.", "abstract": "Government Accountability Office says Environmental Protection Agency's social media campaign urging public to support Obama administration rule meant to better protect country's streams and surface waters was covert and illegal; federal law prohibits agencies from engaging in lobbying efforts; legal opinion emerges at crucial point on spending bill.", "section_name": "U.S.", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Eric", "role": "reported", "lastname": "LIPTON", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}, {"firstname": "Michael", "role": "reported", "rank": 2, "organization": ""}], "original": "By ERIC LIPTON and MICHAEL D. SHEAR"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/15/us/politics/epa-broke-the-law-by-using-social-media-to-push-water-rule-auditor-finds.html", "lead_paragraph": "The agency essentially became a lobbyist for its clean-water cause by directing people to advocacy organizations, the Government Accountability Office said.", "headline": {"main": "E.P.A. Broke Law With Social Media Push for Water Rule, Auditor Finds", "print_headline": "E.P.A. Faulted for Online Blitz on Water Rule"}, "_id": "566f16f638f0d856e6857d37", "word_count": "1202", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/12/15/us/15water-web/15water-web-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/12/15/us/15water-web/15water-web-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 403, "url": "images/2015/12/15/us/15water-web/15water-web-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/12/15/us/15water-web/15water-web-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "403"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/20